# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: basketball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:basketball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The **1936 Summer Olympics** (German: *Olympische Sommerspiele 1936*), officially the **Games of the XI Olympiad** (German: *Spiele der XI.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Olympiade*) and branded as **Berlin 1936**, were an international multi-sport event held from 1 to 16 August 1936 in Berlin, Germany.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Berlin won the right to host the Games over Barcelona at the 29th IOC Session in 1931.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the second and last occasion on which the International Olympic Committee (IOC) chose a host by a ballot in which the bidding cities themselves could vote; later rules barred cities that hosted the vote from being selected.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games had been awarded to Germany during the Weimar Republic, but by 1936 the country was governed by the Nazi regime, and Adolf Hitler's government treated the Olympics as an opportunity for propaganda.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] To project an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signage and softened the most visible forms of persecution for the duration of the Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] At the same time, the German Olympic authorities barred nearly all Jewish and Romani athletes from the national team; the fencer Helene Mayer, who had one Jewish parent, was the only such athlete to represent Germany.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] A movement to boycott or relocate the Games developed in several countries—Czechoslovakia, France, the Netherlands, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States—but it ultimately failed.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, the largest number at any Olympics to that point.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] These were the first Games to be televised and the first to feature a torch relay carrying the Olympic flame from Olympia to the host city—a ceremony devised for Berlin that became a permanent Olympic tradition.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part film *Olympia*, which pioneered techniques still used in sports cinematography.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Jesse Owens of the United States won four gold medals in the sprint and long jump events, and became the most successful athlete to compete in Berlin, while Germany was the most successful country overall with 101 medals (38 of them gold); the United States placed a distant second with 57 medals.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Henri de Baillet-Latour.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] For the next 12 years, no Olympic Games were held due to the immense world disruption caused by the Second World War.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1948 (the Winter Games in St.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Moritz, Switzerland, and then the Summer Games in London, England).
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] At the 28th IOC Session in Berlin in May 1930, fourteen cities indicated an intention to bid for the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] By the 29th Session, held in Barcelona in April 1931, only Barcelona and Berlin remained in contention; the other cities—Alexandria, Budapest, Buenos Aires, Cologne, Dublin, Frankfurt, Helsinki, Lausanne, Montevideo, Nuremberg, Rio de Janeiro, and Rome—had withdrawn.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Several of these cities later hosted the Games: Helsinki in 1952, Rome in 1960, Barcelona in 1992 and Rio de Janeiro in 2016.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the first for which the host was decided by a vote of each individual IOC member rather than by the assembled Session alone.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The deadline for ballots was 13 May 1931, two weeks after the Barcelona Session.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Of 67 voting members, 19 cast ballots during the Session and 40 by post to the IOC headquarters in Lausanne; eight abstained.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The result was 43 votes for Berlin and 16 for Barcelona.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Barcelona's prospects were probably weakened by the political uncertainty that followed the proclamation of the Second Spanish Republic days before the Session.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] After the Nazi seizure of power in 1933 and the regime's early antisemitic measures, some IOC members privately discussed moving the Games, and the US Olympic Association briefly suggested transferring them to Rome.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler's government gave assurances that Jewish athletes would not be excluded from the German team, and the proposal was not seriously pursued.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Awarded to Berlin in 1931 under the Weimar Republic, the Games took on a new character after the Nazi takeover of January 1933, as the regime grasped their value as international propaganda.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler regarded the Games as a chance to promote his government and its ideology of Aryan supremacy.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The official Nazi paper, the *Völkischer Beobachter*, had argued in the strongest terms that Jewish and black athletes should be barred from the Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] As the Games approached, however, the regime worked to soften Germany's international image: signs reading "Jews not welcome" (German: *Juden unerwünscht*) were taken down from public places for the duration, and overt antisemitic agitation was muted.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The effort extended to the removal of people the regime considered undesirable.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In July 1936 the Ministry of the Interior authorised Berlin's police to detain the city's Romani and confine them in a special camp at Marzahn, on the city's outskirts.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Five months before the opening ceremony, in March 1936, Germany had remilitarised the Rhineland in breach of the Treaty of Versailles, heightening international tension in the months before the Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In line with Nazi directives, the German Olympic Committee effectively barred German athletes who were Jewish or Roma, or of such ancestry, from competing.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The most prominent excluded athlete was the high jumper Gretel Bergmann, who was dropped from the team shortly after equalling the German record of 1.60 m in June 1936.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Others kept off the team included the record-holding track-and-field athlete Lilli Henoch, the tennis player Daniel Prenn, the boxer Erich Seelig and the Sinti boxer Johann Trollmann.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Helene Mayer—already an Olympic champion who had emigrated to the United States—returned to fence for Germany and won a silver medal, the only athlete of Jewish descent on the German team, a token inclusion intended to deflect foreign criticism.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The exclusions also reached the organisers.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Although the Olympic flame had been reintroduced at the 1928 Summer Olympics, Berlin staged the first torch relay, carrying a flame kindled at Olympia in Greece to the host city through seven countries.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The concept, organised by Diem, established the modern convention later used at every Games, and Riefenstahl incorporated the relay into *Olympia*.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Olympic Village lay at Elstal in Wustermark, about 30 km west of central Berlin, and comprised low dormitories, a large "Dining Hall of the Nations", training facilities and a swimming hall.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] After the Games the site was absorbed by the Wehrmacht and later used by Soviet forces as a military camp; parts of it, including the dormitory used by Jesse Owens, have been restored more recently.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Twenty-two venues were used, most of them in the purpose-built Reichssportfeld complex, which had been planned for the cancelled 1916 Summer Olympics and was completed in 1934–36.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The centrepiece Olympic Stadium seated about 100,000; sailing was held in the Bay of Kiel, later reused for the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were the first to be carried on live television.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Using Telefunken equipment, the German Post Office transmitted more than 70 hours of black-and-white coverage to public viewing rooms in Berlin and Potsdam, where more than 162,000 people in all followed the competitions on screens outside the stadium.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Radio carried the Games more widely still, in 28 languages across some 2,500 broadcasts.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were also an early showcase for colour photography, using Germany's newly developed Agfacolor film.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part documentary *Olympia*, released in 1938.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were among the most lavish staged to that point, and most of the spending lay well outside the organising committee's own accounts.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] From 1933 the Reich Ministry of the Interior directed a vast building programme that the regime folded into its public-works and job-creation schemes, and historians have treated this state investment—rather than ticket income—as the truer measure of what the Games cost.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Its centrepiece, the new Olympic Stadium, was built in barely two years at a cost of around 42 million Reichsmark; with the wider Reichssportfeld, the Olympic Village and new transport links, the state's outlay dwarfed the committee's budget.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler also prized the Games as a way to earn scarce foreign currency at a time of dwindling German reserves, later claiming they had brought in large sums.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The committee's own books were comparatively modest: ticket sales brought in about 7.5 million RM and an operating profit of over one million RM.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The city of Berlin reported costs of about 16.5 million RM, while the national government's total spending was never published in full and has been estimated at around US$30 million.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The sporting programme ran from 1 to 16 August 1936 and was framed by elaborate opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony took place at the Olympic Stadium on 1 August 1936.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The airship *Hindenburg* flew over the stadium trailing the Olympic flag.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] After Hitler's arrival the parade of nations proceeded, with Greece first and the host nation last; some teams gave the Nazi salute or the similar Olympic salute as they passed Hitler's box, with French Olympians giving a Roman salute, while the United States and a few others did not.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Greek team that led the parade was headed by Spyridon Louis, winner of the marathon at the first modern Olympics in 1896, who presented Hitler with an olive branch from Olympia.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler then declared the Games open; in keeping with Olympic protocol his part was confined to the set formula—"I proclaim the Games of Berlin, celebrating the eleventh Olympiad of the modern era, to be open"—his only public statement during the Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] A torch-bearer then ran into the arena to light the cauldron, and thousands of pigeons were released.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] During the ceremony the Olympic Hymn—specially composed by Richard Strauss, who conducted it himself—received its première; Strauss had taken the commission only after the writer Gerhart Hauptmann failed to supply a text, and he privately dismissed the piece even as he led it.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The programme comprised 129 events in 25 disciplines across 19 sports.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Basketball, canoeing and handball made their Olympic debuts; handball would not return until the 1972 Summer Olympics, while polo made its fifth and final Olympic appearance.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Baseball and gliding were held as demonstration sports, and art competitions awarded medals, as did feats of alpinism and aeronautics recognised at the closing ceremony.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] National strengths were pronounced across the individual sports.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The host nation owed its place atop the medal table chiefly to gymnastics, rowing and the equestrian events, in which German riders won all six golds.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Athletics, the largest sport, was dominated by the United States, whose men won twelve track-and-field golds; Helen Stephens took two of the six women's events.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the pool the men's programme became a duel between the US and Japan, while Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands, the outstanding swimmer of the Games, led Dutch dominance of the women's events; US women instead won both diving titles.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] France's Robert Charpentier won three cycling golds, and the fencing titles fell mainly to Italy and Hungary.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The team events produced their own milestones.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The United States won the first Olympic basketball tournament, beating Canada 19–8 in a final played outdoors on a rain-soaked clay court, with the game's inventor James Naismith on hand to present the medals.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Germany won the inaugural field handball competition, an eleven-a-side outdoor game, and Hungary took the water polo, a sport it would go on to dominate.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Italy won the football and India a third successive hockey gold, while polo, won by Argentina, was contested for the last time.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The outstanding individual performer was Jesse Owens of the United States, who won gold in the 100 m, 200 m, long jump, and 4×100 m relay.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the long jump his German rival Luz Long offered him advice after he nearly failed to qualify, and the two were publicly cordial.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Mack Robinson, brother of Jackie Robinson, took 200 m silver behind Owens.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the 800 m, John Woodruff won gold after deliberately slowing to free himself when boxed in.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Jack Lovelock of New Zealand won the 1500 m in a world-record 3:47.8.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Glenn Morris of the United States set a world record of 7,900 points to lead an American medal sweep, and Ondina Valla took the 80 m hurdles to become the first Italian woman to win an Olympic title, in a final so close that the first four finishers were given the same time.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] German athletes were strong in several sports, sweeping all six equestrian golds and, in the gymnasts Konrad Frey and Alfred Schwarzmann, producing two triple gold medallists.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The equestrian team eventing title owed much to Konrad von Wangenheim, who finished the cross-country phase despite breaking his collarbone in a fall and returned the next day—his arm in a sling—to complete the jumping after he and his horse fell again.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands won three swimming golds and a silver, and the Estonian Kristjan Palusalu became the only wrestler to win both the freestyle and Greco-Roman heavyweight titles at a single Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Egyptian weightlifter Khadr El Touni won the middleweight gold with a world-record total, beating the German silver medallist by a wide margin.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the football tournament, Italy—coached by Vittorio Pozzo between their two FIFA World Cup wins—took gold; the result was claimed by supporters of Benito Mussolini as a vindication of fascism.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Peru had beaten Austria 4–2 after extra time amid a disputed pitch invasion, but the IOC ordered a replay behind closed doors; Peru refused and withdrew from the Games, as did Colombia in sympathy.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] On its Olympic football debut, Japan came from two goals down to beat the favoured Swedes 3–2 before being eliminated by Italy in the next round.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] India won its third consecutive hockey gold, defeating Germany 8–1 in the final.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In the marathon, the Korean runners Sohn Kee-chung and Nam Sung-yong won gold and bronze while competing for Japan, which then ruled Korea.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] More than half a century later, Sohn carried the Olympic flame into the stadium at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The United States eight, from the University of Washington, won the rowing title with a come-from-behind final, later recounted in *The Boys in the Boat*.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The 13-year-old US Marjorie Gestring won the 3 m springboard, and Betty Robinson, the 1928 100 m champion who had nearly died in a 1931 plane crash, returned to win gold in the 4×100 m relay.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The American Jewish sprinters Marty Glickman and Sam Stoller were dropped from the 4×100 m relay on the morning of the race in favour of Owens and Ralph Metcalfe; the decision has been widely attributed to a wish not to embarrass the German hosts, though the reasons remain disputed.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games closed on the evening of 16 August 1936 before a crowd of more than 100,000 in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Historians have described the closing as more sombre and militaristic than the opening, marked by columns of soldiers and fireworks.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] As the ceremony reached its climax, searchlights ringed the arena to form a "dome of light" overhead, the five-ringed Olympic flag was slowly lowered, and the flame that had burned since 1 August was extinguished as the spectators joined in a closing choral hymn.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour formally declared the Games closed.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympics of his presidency and, as it proved, the last for twelve years; the 1940 Games had already been awarded to Tokyo at the IOC session held in Berlin on 31 July 1936, before the Olympics even opened.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Two unusual special awards were also recognised in connection with the closing.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] An Olympic gold for alpinism went to the mountaineers Günter and Hettie Dyhrenfurth for their Himalayan expeditions, and the only Olympic gold ever awarded for aeronautics went to the Swiss pilot Hermann Schreiber for the first glider flight across the Alps; neither prize was contested again.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, up from 37 in 1932.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Five made their first Olympic appearance: Afghanistan, Bermuda, Bolivia, Costa Rica and Liechtenstein.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Several nations returned after missing 1932, while Ireland and Spain competed in 1932 but were absent from Berlin.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Sources give the number of participants differently, largely because of how the art competitions are counted.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives the figure of 3,963 athletes—3,632 men and 331 women—in the sporting events.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The twelve nations that won the most medals at the 1936 Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] As at every Games from 1912 to 1948, medals were also awarded in art competitions for works inspired by sport.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 edition was the largest the Olympics ever staged, with fifteen events across five categories—architecture, literature, music, painting and sculpture—and the entries were shown in an exhibition on the Kaiserdamm that drew some 70,000 visitors.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] A novelty that year was that the prize-winning musical works were performed: the German composer Werner Egk took the orchestral gold for his *Olympic Festive Music*.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] With many French and British artists staying away, German entrants dominated, winning twelve of the thirty-two medals and five of the nine golds; the judges withheld medals entirely in three events.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The art competitions were dropped after 1948; the IOC's currently recognizes them as official and its database give Germany a combined total of 101 medals for the 1936 Games, which includes 12 medals won in art competitions.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Prior to and during the Games, there was considerable debate outside Germany over whether the competition should be allowed or discontinued.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] A number of campaigns to boycott or relocate the Games emerged in the United Kingdom, France, Sweden, Czechoslovakia, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The most consequential debate took place in the United States.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The protests were ultimately unsuccessful; forty-nine teams from around the world participated in the 1936 Games, the largest number of participating nations of any Olympics to that point.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Traditionally, the US sent one of the largest teams to the Olympics, and there was a considerable debate over whether the nation should participate in the 1936 Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Americans Milton Green and Norman Cahners refused to attend, and American Jewish organizations, such as the American Jewish Congress and the Jewish Labor Committee, supported a boycott.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney, president of the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU), contested that racial discrimination was a violation of Olympic rules and that participation in the Games was amount to an indirect endorsement of the Third Reich.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Avery Brundage, then of the American Olympic Committee, opposed the boycott, maintaining that politics had no place in sport and that the Olympic movement would be undermined if nations restricted participation by race or creed.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Brundage would be later accused of being a Soviet sympathizer for his controversial stance on the Soviet sports system that allowed them to circumvent the amateur rules.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Most African-American newspapers supported participation in the Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Philadelphia *Tribune* and the *Chicago Defender* both agreed that black victories would undermine Nazi views of Aryan supremacy and spark renewed African-American pride.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Eventually, Brundage won the debate, convincing the Amateur Athletic Union to close a vote in favor of sending an American team to the Berlin Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney's efforts to incite a boycott of the Olympic games in the United States failed, although some athletes like Harvard University track star Milton Green chose to sit at home.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] US President Franklin Roosevelt and his administration did not become involved in the debate, due to a tradition of allowing the Olympic Committee to operate independently of government influence.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Several American diplomats including William E.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Dodd, the American ambassador to Berlin, and George Messersmith, head of the US legation in Vienna, opposed the decision to participate in the games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Jewish Labour Committee staged a "World Labour Athletic Carnival" in New York during as an alternative sporting event.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Spanish government led by the newly elected left-wing Popular Front boycotted the Games and the Government of Catalonia organized the People's Olympiad as a parallel event in Barcelona.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Some 6,000 athletes from 49 countries registered.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] However, the People's Olympiad was aborted because of the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War just one day before the event was due to start.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had not participated in international sporting events since the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet government was not invited to the 1920 Games, with the Russian Civil War still raging, and they did not participate in the 1924 Summer Olympics and forward on ideological grounds.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Instead, through the auspices of the Red Sport International, it had participated in a left-wing workers' alternative, the Spartakiad, since 1928.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The USSR had intended to attend the People's Olympiad in Barcelona until it was cancelled; the Soviets did attend the Spartakiad-sponsored 1937 Workers' Summer Olympiad in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union started competing in the Olympics in 1952, when Joseph Stalin realized that they could use the event to fulfil their political and ideological agenda.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] In France, the Jewish fencer Albert Wolff qualified for the national team but withdrew on principle.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Maccabi World Union declined an invitation on behalf of Mandatory Palestine, and two Turkish fencers, Halet Çambel and Suat Fetgeri Aşani—among the first Muslim women to compete at the Olympics—reportedly refused an introduction to Hitler.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Historians widely regard the Berlin Games as a major propaganda success for the Nazi regime, though they differ over how far that success reached.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The US Holocaust Memorial Museum describes them as "a resounding propaganda success" that projected an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, and notes that the forty-nine nations who took part lent the regime legitimacy in the eyes of both foreign and domestic audiences.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Most contemporary press coverage was favourable; US newspapers echoed a *New York Times* report that the Games had put Germany "back in the fold of nations".
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Astute diplomats and correspondents stationed in Germany were less easily fooled, but many ordinary visitors and much of the foreign media came away impressed.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Mandell, in the first major English-language study, *The Nazi Olympics* (1971), argued that the regime's unprecedented mass pageantry overwhelmed the critical judgement of visiting journalists, businessmen and diplomats.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Other historians stress that the result turned on the failure of the boycott movement and on the willingness of officials to accept the regime's assurances, rather than on propaganda alone.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's four gold medals became the most enduring popular memory of the Games and were widely seen as a rebuke to Nazi racial theory, though Germany still finished well clear at the top of the medal table.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Owens said he had been treated cordially in Germany and reserved his bitterness for the segregation he faced on returning home, noting that President Franklin D.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Roosevelt neither received nor congratulated him.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The image of a tolerant Germany did not outlast the Games.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Once the foreign visitors had left, anti-Jewish measures resumed and persecution intensified, leading to the Kristallnacht pogrom of November 1938 and, in September 1939, the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Several 1936 Olympians were later murdered in the Holocaust, among them the Polish competitors Roman Kantor and Ilia Szrajbman, both killed at Majdanek.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The war forced the cancellation of the 1940 and 1944 Games, and the Olympics did not resume until London 1948.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Games left a lasting cultural and sporting imprint.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Leni Riefenstahl's film *Olympia* (1938) is regarded both as a landmark in cinema—for innovations such as underwater and slow-motion photography that influenced later sports filmmaking—and as a work of state propaganda.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The torch relay and the live television coverage introduced in Berlin became permanent features of the modern Games, and the Olympic Stadium survived the war to be renovated for the 2006 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's story has since been dramatised on film, including in *Race* (2016).
[src:basketball/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin Games are now widely cited as the archetypal example of "sportswashing"—the use of a prestigious sporting event to improve the image of an authoritarian government—and as a precedent in debates over later host selections.
[src:basketball/1956-57-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] The **1956–57 Tennessee A&I State Tigers basketball team** represented Tennessee A&I State College (now called Tennessee State University) in National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) men's basketball during the 1956–57 season.
[src:basketball/1956-57-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] Coached by third-year head coach John McLendon, the Tigers finished the season with a 31–4 record and were crowned NAIA national champions by winning the 1957 NAIA tournament.
[src:basketball/1956-57-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] This marked the first of three consecutive national championships, a feat that no other team at any level of college basketball had previously accomplished.
[src:basketball/1956-57-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] In addition, the 1956–57 team became the first historically black college to win a national basketball title.
[src:basketball/1956-57-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] In 2019, all three national championship teams were inducted into the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame.
[src:basketball/1957-58-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] The **1957–58 Tennessee A&I State Tigers basketball team** represented Tennessee A&I State College (now called Tennessee State University) in National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) men's basketball during the 1957–58 season.
[src:basketball/1957-58-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] Coached by fourth-year head coach John McLendon, the Tigers finished the season with a 31–3 record and were crowned NAIA national champions by winning the 1958 NAIA tournament.
[src:basketball/1957-58-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] This marked the second of three consecutive national championships, a feat that no other team at any level of college basketball had previously accomplished.
[src:basketball/1958-59-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] The **1958–59 Tennessee A&I State Tigers basketball team** represented Tennessee A&I State College (now called Tennessee State University) in National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) men's basketball during the 1958–59 season.
[src:basketball/1958-59-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] Coached by fifth-year head coach John McLendon, the Tigers finished the season with a school-record 32 wins and were crowned NAIA national champions by winning the 1959 NAIA tournament.
[src:basketball/1958-59-tennessee-a-i-state-tigers-basketball-team] This marked the third of three consecutive national championships, a feat that no other team at any level of college basketball had previously accomplished.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The **1960 United States men's Olympic basketball team** competed in the Games of the XVII Olympiad in Rome, Italy, representing the United States of America.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The USA team, coached by California Golden Bears head coach Pete Newell, dominated the competition, winning its games by an average of 42.4 points per game.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The team is considered by many to be the best amateur level basketball team of all time, and was elected to the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame as a unit, in 2010.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Trials for the team were held in March and April 1960, in Denver, at the Denver Coliseum.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The NCAA All-Stars won the competition convincingly, and so Pete Newell was named the team's head coach, with Warren Womble as his assistant.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The trials came at a time when the AAU and NCAA were wrestling for control of USA Basketball, and the make-up of the team represented that uneasy truce, as the team was made up of seven collegiate stars, four AAU players, and one representative of the US Armed Forces (guard Adrian Smith).
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] This compromise meant that many top college players were left off the team, including Ohio State's John Havlicek and Providence guard Lenny Wilkens.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The team went 8–0 in the Olympic basketball tournament, held in Rome, averaging 101.9 points per game and holding their opponents to 59.5.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Five Americans averaged double-figures in scoring - Oscar Robertson (17.3), Jerry Lucas (16.8), Jerry West (14.1), Terry Dischinger (11.3) and Adrian Smith (10.9).
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Lucas was the star of the medal round, as he scored 21 points in the gold medal game against Brazil, after having scored 26 points in the previous game against host Italy.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The 1960 team is thought to be one of the best amateur sports teams in basketball history.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Other career distinctions by team members include Robertson's League MVP Award in 1963–64.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Dischinger's 1963 NBA Rookie of the Year Award (an award also received by Robertson (1961), Bellamy (1962), and Lucas(1964), Adrian Smith's NBA All-Star Game MVP in 1966, and West's NBA Finals MVP in 1969.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] Eight members were later selected to at least one NBA All-Star Game (Bob Boozer, Darrall Imhoff and Adrian Smith were NBA All-Star Game participants during their careers.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] In total, there were 43 future All-Star berths amongst the teammates.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] In 2010, along with the "Dream Team," the 1960 US Olympic men's basketball team was elected to the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame as a unit.
[src:basketball/1960-united-states-men-s-olympic-basketball-team] The election marks only the seventh and eighth teams so honored.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The **1965–66 Texas Western Miners basketball team** represented Texas Western College, now the University of Texas at El Paso (UTEP), led by Hall of Fame head coach Don Haskins.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The team won the national championship in 1966, becoming the first team with an all-black starting lineup to do so.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The Miners only lost one game, a road loss to Seattle by two points.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] They won their games by an average of 15.2 points.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The Miners beat Kentucky (an all-white program until 1969) 72–65 in the historic championship game, played on Saturday, March 19, at Cole Field House on the University of Maryland campus in College Park, a suburb of Washington, D.C.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The team was inducted into the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame in 2007 and inspired the book and film *Glory Road*.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] The 1965–66 Texas Western basketball team faced many issues due to racism.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] For example, when they won the championship no one brought out a ladder for them to cut down the net.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] Nevil Shed had to hoist up Willie Worsley so he could do the honors.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] Also, they were not invited on *The Ed Sullivan Show*, which was customary for the NCAA Champions.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] Texas Western's (UTEP's) winning the basketball national championship helped promote the desegregation of athletics in the Southeastern Conference which had its first black basketball player in 1967.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] As for their professional outlooks following this season, only one of the players from this team (David Lattin) would end up playing in the NBA, being selected as a Top 10 pick by the San Francisco Warriors in the 1967 NBA draft.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] Another player named Willie Worsley would later join the ABA, though he would play for the New York Nets in only the second season of the ABA's existence before retiring altogether.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] A couple of other players in Willie Cager and Nevil Shed would also get drafted in the NBA as well, though unlike with Lattin, neither would play in the NBA properly.
[src:basketball/1965-66-texas-western-miners-men-s-basketball-team] Finally, the rest of the roster would not even touch the NBA or the ABA themselves following this season onward.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Players advance the ball by bouncing it while walking or running (dribbling) or by passing it to a teammate, both of which require considerable skill.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] On offense, players may use a variety of shots – the layup, the jump shot, or a dunk.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] On defense, they may steal the ball from a dribbler, intercept passes, or block shots.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Either offense, or defense may collect a rebound, which is a missed shot that bounces from rim or backboard.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] It is a violation to lift or drag one's pivot foot without dribbling the ball, to carry it, or to hold the ball with both hands then resume dribbling.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The five players on each side fall into five playing positions.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The tallest player is typically the center, the second-tallest and strongest is the power forward.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The small forward is a shorter, but very agile player.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Lastly, the shortest players or the best ball handlers are the shooting guard and the point guard.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These players implement the coach's game plan by managing the execution of offensive and defensive plays (player positioning).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Informally, players may play three-on-three, two-on-two, and one-on-one.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Invented in 1891 by Canadian-American gym teacher James Naismith in Springfield, Massachusetts, in the United States, basketball has evolved to become one of the world's most popular and widely viewed sports.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the most significant professional basketball league in the world in terms of popularity, salaries, talent, and level of competition (drawing most of its talent from U.S. college basketball).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Outside North America, the top clubs from national leagues qualify to continental championships such as the EuroLeague and the Basketball Champions League Americas.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The FIBA Basketball World Cup and Men's Olympic Basketball Tournament are the major international events of the sport and attract top national teams from around the world.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Each continent hosts regional competitions for national teams, like EuroBasket and FIBA AmeriCup.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup and women's Olympic basketball tournament feature top national teams from continental championships.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The main North American league is the WNBA (NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship is also popular), whereas the strongest European clubs participate in the EuroLeague Women.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In December 1891, James Naismith, a Canadian-American professor of physical education and instructor at the International Young Men's Christian Association Training School (now Springfield College) in Springfield, Massachusetts, was trying to keep his gym class active on a rainy day.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] He sought a vigorous indoor game to keep his students occupied and at proper levels of fitness during the long New England winters.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] After rejecting other ideas as either too rough or poorly suited to walled-in gymnasiums, he invented a new game in which players would pass a ball to teammates and try to score points by tossing the ball into a basket mounted on a wall.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith wrote the basic rules and nailed a peach basket onto an elevated track.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith initially set up the peach basket with its bottom intact, which meant that the ball had to be retrieved manually after each "basket" or point scored.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] This quickly proved tedious, so Naismith removed the bottom of the basket to allow the balls to be poked out with a long dowel after each scored basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Shortly after, Senda Berenson, instructor of physical culture at the nearby Smith College, went to Naismith to learn more about the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Fascinated by the new sport and the values it could teach, she started to organize games with her pupils, following adjusted rules.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first official women's interinstitutional game was played barely 11 months later, between the University of California and Miss Head's School.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1899, a committee was established at the Conference of Physical Training in Springfield to draw up general rules for women's basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Thus, the sport quickly spread throughout America's schools, colleges and universities with uniform rules for both sexes.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Basketball was originally played with a soccer ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These round balls from "association football" were made, at the time, with a set of laces to close off the hole needed for inserting the inflatable bladder after the other sewn-together segments of the ball's cover had been flipped outside-in.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These laces could cause bounce passes and dribbling to be unpredictable.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Eventually a lace-free ball construction method was invented, and this change to the game was endorsed by Naismith (whereas in American football, the lace construction proved to be advantageous for gripping and remains to this day).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first balls made specifically for basketball were brown, and it was only in the late 1950s that Tony Hinkle, searching for a ball that would be more visible to players and spectators alike, introduced the orange ball that is now in common use.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Dribbling was not part of the original game except for the "bounce pass" to teammates.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Passing the ball was the primary means of ball movement.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Dribbling was eventually introduced but limited by the asymmetric shape of early balls.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Dribbling was common by 1896, with a rule against the double dribble by 1898.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The peach baskets were used until 1906 when they were finally replaced by metal hoops with backboards.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A further change was soon made, so the ball merely passed through.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Whenever a person got the ball in the basket, their team would gain a point.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Whichever team got the most points won the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The baskets were originally nailed to the mezzanine balcony of the playing court, but this proved impractical when spectators in the balcony began to interfere with shots.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The backboard was introduced to prevent this interference; it had the additional effect of allowing rebound shots.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith's handwritten diaries, discovered by his granddaughter in early 2006, indicate that he was nervous about the new game he had invented, which incorporated rules from a children's game called duck on a rock, as many had failed before it.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Frank Mahan, one of the players from the original first game, approached Naismith after the Christmas break, in early 1892, asking him what he intended to call his new game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith replied that he had not thought of it because he had been focused on just getting the game started.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Mahan suggested that it be called "Naismith ball", at which he laughed, saying that a name like that would kill any game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Mahan then said, "Why not call it basketball?" Naismith replied, "We have a basket and a ball, and it seems to me that would be a good name for it." The first official game was played in the YMCA gymnasium in Albany, New York, on January 20, 1892, with nine players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The game ended at 1–0; the shot was made from 25 feet (7.6 m), on a court just half the size of a present-day Streetball or National Basketball Association (NBA) court.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] At the time, soccer was being played with 10 to a team (which was increased to 11).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] When winter weather got too icy to play soccer, teams were taken indoors, and it was convenient to have them split in half and play basketball with five on each side.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] By 1897–98, teams of five became standard.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Basketball's early adherents were dispatched to YMCAs throughout the United States, and it quickly spread through the United States and Canada.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] By 1895, it was well established at several women's high schools.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] While YMCA was responsible for initially developing and spreading the game, within a decade it discouraged the new sport, as rough play and rowdy crowds began to detract from YMCA's primary mission.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] However, other amateur sports clubs, colleges, and professional clubs quickly filled the void.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the years before World War I, the Amateur Athletic Union and the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (forerunner of the NCAA) vied for control over the rules for the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first pro league, the National Basketball League, was formed in 1898 to protect players from exploitation and to promote a less rough game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] James Naismith was instrumental in establishing college basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Beamis fielded the first college basketball team just a year after the Springfield YMCA game at the suburban Pittsburgh Geneva College.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith himself later coached at the University of Kansas for six years, before handing the reins to renowned coach Forrest "Phog" Allen.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naismith's disciple Amos Alonzo Stagg brought basketball to the University of Chicago, while Adolph Rupp, a student of Naismith's at Kansas, enjoyed great success as coach at the University of Kentucky.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] On February 9, 1895, the first intercollegiate 5-on-5 game was played at Hamline University between Hamline and the School of Agriculture, which was affiliated with the University of Minnesota.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The School of Agriculture won in a 9–3 game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1901, colleges, including the University of Chicago, Columbia University, Cornell University, Dartmouth College, the University of Minnesota, the U.S.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Naval Academy, the University of Colorado and Yale University began sponsoring men's games.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1905, frequent injuries on the football field prompted President Theodore Roosevelt to suggest that colleges form a governing body, resulting in the creation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (IAAUS).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1910, that body changed its name to the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first Canadian interuniversity basketball game was played at YMCA in Kingston, Ontario on February 6, 1904, when McGill University – Naismith's alma mater – visited Queen's University.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] McGill won 9–7 in overtime; the score was 7–7 at the end of regulation play, and a ten-minute overtime period settled the outcome.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A good turnout of spectators watched the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first men's national championship tournament, the National Association of Intercollegiate Basketball tournament, which still exists as the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) tournament, was organized in 1937.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first national championship for NCAA teams, the National Invitation Tournament (NIT) in New York, was organized in 1938; the NCAA national tournament began one year later.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] College basketball was rocked by gambling scandals from 1948 to 1951, when dozens of players from top teams were implicated in game-fixing and point shaving.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Partially spurred by an association with cheating, the NIT lost support to the NCAA tournament.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Before widespread school district consolidation, most American high schools were far smaller than their present-day counterparts.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] During the first decades of the 20th century, basketball quickly became the ideal interscholastic sport due to its modest equipment and personnel requirements.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the days before widespread television coverage of professional and college sports, the popularity of high school basketball was unrivaled in many parts of America.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Perhaps the most legendary of high school teams was Indiana's Franklin Wonder Five, which took the nation by storm during the 1920s, dominating Indiana basketball and earning national recognition.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Today virtually every high school in the United States fields a basketball team in varsity competition.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Basketball's popularity remains high, both in rural areas where they carry the identification of the entire community, as well as at some larger schools known for their basketball teams where many players go on to participate at higher levels of competition after graduation.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the 2016–17 season, 980,673 boys and girls represented their schools in interscholastic basketball competition, according to the National Federation of State High School Associations.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The states of Illinois, Indiana, and Kentucky are particularly well known for their residents' devotion to high school basketball, commonly called Hoosier Hysteria in Indiana; the critically acclaimed film *Hoosiers* shows high school basketball's depth of meaning to these communities.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] ⁣There is currently no tournament to determine a national high school champion.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The most serious effort was the National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament at the University of Chicago from 1917 to 1930.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The event was organized by Amos Alonzo Stagg and sent invitations to state champion teams.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The tournament started out as a mostly Midwest affair but grew.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Faced with opposition from the National Federation of State High School Associations and North Central Association of Colleges and Schools that bore a threat of the schools losing their accreditation the last tournament was in 1930.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The organizations said they were concerned that the tournament was being used to recruit professional players from the prep ranks.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The tournament did not invite minority schools or private/parochial schools.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Interscholastic Basketball Tournament ran from 1924 to 1941 at Loyola University.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Invitational Basketball Tournament from 1954 to 1978 played at a series of venues, including Catholic University, Georgetown and George Mason.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament for Black High Schools was held from 1929 to 1942 at Hampton Institute.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The National Invitational Interscholastic Basketball Tournament was held from 1941 to 1967 starting out at Tuskegee Institute.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Following a pause during World War II it resumed at Tennessee State College in Nashville.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The basis for the champion dwindled after 1954 when *Brown v.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Board of Education* began an integration of schools.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The last tournaments were held at Alabama State College from 1964 to 1967.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] There were hundreds of men's professional basketball teams in towns and cities all over the United States, and little organization of the professional game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Players jumped from team to team and teams played in armories and smoky dance halls.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Barnstorming squads such as the Original Celtics and two all-African American teams, the New York Renaissance Five ("Rens") and the (still existing) Harlem Globetrotters played up to two hundred games a year on their national tours.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1946, the Basketball Association of America (BAA) was formed.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first game was played in Toronto, Ontario, Canada between the Toronto Huskies and New York Knickerbockers on November 1, 1946.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Three seasons later, in 1949, the BAA merged with the National Basketball League (NBL) to form the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] By the 1950s, basketball had become a major college sport, thus paving the way for a growth of interest in professional basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1959, a basketball hall of fame was founded in Springfield, Massachusetts, site of the first game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Its rosters include the names of great players, coaches, referees and people who have contributed significantly to the development of the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The hall of fame has people who have accomplished many goals in their career in basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] An upstart organization, the American Basketball Association, emerged in 1967 and briefly threatened the NBA's dominance until the ABA-NBA merger in 1976.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Today the NBA is the top professional basketball league in the world in terms of popularity, salaries, talent, and level of competition.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The NBA has featured many famous players, including; George "Big Man" Mikan, ball-handling wizard Bob Cousy, defensive pro Bill Russell and the charismatic center, Wilt Chamberlain.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] All-around stars include; Oscar Robertson and Jerry West, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Shaquille O'Neal, Hakeem Olajuwon, and Karl Malone.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Other star playmakers like John Stockton, Isiah Thomas and Steve Nash.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Notable crowd-pleasing forwards are Julius Erving and Charles Barkley.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The list include European stars; Dirk Nowitzki, Pau Gasol, Nikola Jokić, and Tony Parker; Latin American star Manu Ginobili, and modern pro-superstars like Allen Iverson, Kobe Bryant, Tim Duncan, LeBron James, Stephen Curry, Giannis Antetokounmpo, and many more.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The three players who many credit with ushering the professional game to its highest level of popularity during the 1980s and 1990s: Larry Bird, Earvin "Magic" Johnson, and Michael Jordan.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 2001, the NBA formed a developmental league, the National Basketball Development League (later known as the NBA D-League and then the NBA G League after a branding deal with Gatorade).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] As of the 2023–24 season, the G League has 31 teams.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] FIBA (International Basketball Federation) was formed in 1932 by eight founding nations: Argentina, Czechoslovakia, Greece, Italy, Latvia, Portugal, Romania, and Switzerland.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] At this time, the organization only oversaw amateur players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Its acronym, derived from the French *Fédération Internationale de Basket-ball Amateur*, was thus "FIBA".
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Men's basketball was first included at the Berlin 1936 Summer Olympics, although a demonstration tournament was held in 1904.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The United States defeated Canada in the first final, played outdoors.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] This competition has usually been dominated by the United States, whose team has won all but three titles.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first of these came in a controversial final game in Munich in 1972 against the Soviet Union, in which the ending of the game was replayed three times until the Soviet Union finally came out on top.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1950, the first FIBA World Championship for men, now known as the FIBA Basketball World Cup, was held in Argentina.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Three years later, the first FIBA World Championship for women, now known as the FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup, was held in Chile.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Women's basketball was added to the Olympics in 1976, which were held in Montreal, Quebec, Canada with teams such as the Soviet Union, Brazil, and Australia rivaling the American squads.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1989, FIBA allowed professional NBA players to participate in the Olympics for the first time.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Prior to the 1992 Summer Olympics, only European and South American teams were allowed to field professionals in the Olympics.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The United States' dominance continued with the introduction of the original Dream Team.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the 2004 Athens Olympics, the United States suffered its first Olympic loss while using professional players, falling to Puerto Rico (in a 19-point loss) and Lithuania in group games, and being eliminated in the semifinals by Argentina.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] It eventually won the bronze medal defeating Lithuania, finishing behind Argentina and Italy.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Redeem Team, won gold at the 2008 Olympics, and the B-Team, won gold at the 2010 FIBA World Championship in Turkey despite featuring no players from the 2008 squad.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The United States continued its dominance as they won gold at the 2012 Olympics, 2014 FIBA World Cup, 2016 Olympics, 2020 Olympics, and 2024 Olympics.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Worldwide, basketball tournaments are held for boys and girls of all age levels.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The global popularity of the sport is reflected in the nationalities represented in the NBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Players from all six inhabited continents currently play in the NBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Top international players began coming into the NBA in the mid-1990s, including Croatians Dražen Petrović and Toni Kukoč, Serbian Vlade Divac, Lithuanians Arvydas Sabonis and Šarūnas Marčiulionis, Dutchman Rik Smits, and German Detlef Schrempf.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the Philippines, the Philippine Basketball Association's first game was played on April 9, 1975, at the Araneta Coliseum in Cubao, Quezon City, Philippines.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] It was founded as a "rebellion" of several teams from the now-defunct Manila Industrial and Commercial Athletic Association, which was tightly controlled by the Basketball Association of the Philippines (now defunct), the then-FIBA recognized national association.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Nine teams from the MICAA participated in the league's first season that opened on April 9, 1975.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The NBL is Australia's pre-eminent men's professional basketball league.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The league commenced in 1979, playing a winter season (April–September) and did so until the completion of the 20th season in 1998.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The 1998–99 season, which commenced only months later, was the first season after the shift to the current summer season format (October–April).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] This shift was an attempt to avoid competing directly against Australia's various football codes.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] It features eight teams from around Australia and one in New Zealand.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A few players including Luc Longley, Andrew Gaze, Shane Heal, Chris Anstey, and Andrew Bogut made it big internationally, becoming poster figures for the sport in Australia.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Women's National Basketball League began in 1981.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Women began to play basketball in the fall of 1892 at Smith College through Senda Berenson, substitute director of the newly opened gymnasium and physical education teacher, after having modified the rules for women.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Shortly after Berenson was hired at Smith, she visited Naismith to learn more about the game.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Fascinated by the new sport and the values it could teach, she instantly introduced the game as a class exercise and soon after teams were organized.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first women's collegiate basketball game was played on March 21, 1893, when her Smith freshmen and sophomores played against one another.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first official women's interinstitutional game was played later that year between the University of California and the Miss Head's School.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These rules, designed by Berenson, were published in 1899.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1902 Berenson became the editor of A.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Spalding's first Women's Basketball Guide.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The same year women of Mount Holyoke and Sophie Newcomb College (coached by Clara Gregory Baer), began playing basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] By 1895, the game had spread to colleges across the country, including Wellesley, Vassar, and Bryn Mawr.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first intercollegiate women's game was on April 4, 1896.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Stanford women played Berkeley, 9-on-9, ending in a 2–1 Stanford victory.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Women's basketball development was more structured than that for men in the early years.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 1905, the executive committee on Basket Ball Rules (National Women's Basketball Committee) was created by the American Physical Education Association.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These rules called for six to nine players per team and 11 officials.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The International Women's Sports Federation (1924) included a women's basketball competition.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] 37 women's high school varsity basketball or state tournaments were held by 1925.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] And in 1926, the Amateur Athletic Union backed the first national women's basketball championship, complete with men's rules.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Edmonton Grads, a touring Canadian women's team based in Edmonton, Alberta, operated between 1915 and 1940.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Grads toured all over North America, and were exceptionally successful.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] They posted a record of 522 wins and only 20 losses over that span, as they met any team that wanted to challenge them, funding their tours from gate receipts.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Grads also shone on several exhibition trips to Europe, and won four consecutive exhibition Olympics tournaments, in 1924, 1928, 1932, and 1936; however, women's basketball was not an official Olympic sport until 1976.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Grads' players were unpaid, and had to remain single.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The Grads' style focused on team play, without overly emphasizing skills of individual players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The first women's AAU All-America team was chosen in 1929.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Women's industrial leagues sprang up throughout the United States, producing famous athletes, including Babe Didrikson of the Golden Cyclones, and the All American Red Heads Team, which competed against men's teams, using men's rules.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] By 1938, the women's national championship changed from a three-court game to two-court game with six players per team.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The NBA-backed Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA) began in 1997.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Though it had shaky attendance figures, several marquee players (Lisa Leslie, Diana Taurasi, Sue Bird, and Candace Parker among others) have helped the league's popularity and level of competition.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Other professional women's basketball leagues in the United States, such as the American Basketball League (1996–98), have folded in part because of the popularity of the WNBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The WNBA has been looked at by many as a niche league.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] However, the league has recently taken steps forward.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In June 2007, the WNBA signed a contract extension with ESPN.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The new television deal ran from 2009 to 2016.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Along with this deal, came the first-ever rights fees to be paid to a women's professional sports league.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Over the eight years of the contract, "millions and millions of dollars" were "dispersed to the league's teams." In a March 12, 2009, article, NBA commissioner David Stern said that in the bad economy, "the NBA is far less profitable than the WNBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] We're losing a lot of money among a large number of teams.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Measurements and time limits discussed in this section often vary among tournaments and organizations; international and NBA rules are used in this section.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The object of the game is to outscore one's opponents by throwing the ball through the opponents' basket from above while preventing the opponents from doing so on their own.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] An attempt to score in this way is called a shot.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A successful shot is worth two points, or three points if it is taken from beyond the three-point arc 6.75 meters (22 ft 2 in) from the basket in international games and 23 feet 9 inches (7.24 m) in NBA games.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A one-point shot can be earned when shooting from the foul line after a foul is made.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] After a team has scored from a field goal or free throw, play is resumed with a **throw-in** awarded to the non-scoring team taken from a point beyond the endline of the court where the points were scored.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Games are played in four quarters of 10 (FIBA) or 12 minutes (NBA).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] College men's games use two 20-minute halves, college women's games use 10-minute quarters, and most United States high school varsity games use 8-minute quarters; however, this varies from state to state.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] 15 minutes are allowed for a half-time break under FIBA, NBA, and NCAA rules and 10 minutes in United States high schools.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Overtime periods are five minutes in length except for high school, which is four minutes in length.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Teams exchange baskets for the second half.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The time allowed is actual playing time; the clock is stopped while the play is not active.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Therefore, games generally take much longer to complete than the allotted game time, typically about two hours.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Five players from each team may be on the court at one time.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Substitutions are unlimited but can only be done when play is stopped.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Teams also have a coach, who oversees the development and strategies of the team, and other team personnel such as assistant coaches, managers, statisticians, doctors and trainers.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] For both men's and women's teams, a standard uniform consists of a pair of shorts and a jersey with a clearly visible number, unique within the team, printed on both the front and back.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A limited number of time-outs, clock stoppages requested by a coach (or sometimes mandated in the NBA) for a short meeting with the players, are allowed.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] They generally last no longer than one minute (100 seconds in the NBA) unless, for televised games, a commercial break is needed.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The game is controlled by the officials consisting of the referee (referred to as crew chief in the NBA), one or two umpires (referred to as referees in the NBA) and the table officials.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] For college, the NBA, and many high schools, there are a total of three referees on the court.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The table officials are responsible for keeping track of each team's scoring, timekeeping, individual and team fouls, player substitutions, team possession arrow, and the shot clock.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The only essential equipment in a basketball game is the ball and the court: a flat, rectangular surface with baskets at opposite ends.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Competitive levels require the use of more equipment such as clocks, score sheets, scoreboards, alternating possession arrows, and whistle-operated stop-clock systems.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A regulation basketball court in international games is 28 meters (92 feet) long and 15 meters (49 feet) wide.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the NBA and NCAA, the court is 94 by 50 feet (29 by 15 meters).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Most courts have wood flooring, usually constructed from maple planks running in the same direction as the longer court dimension.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The name and logo of the home team is usually painted on or around the center circle.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The basket is a steel rim 18 inches (46 cm) diameter with an attached net affixed to a backboard that measures 6 by 3.5 feet (1.8 by 1.1 meters) and one basket is at each end of the court.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The white outlined box on the backboard is 18 inches (46 cm) high and 2 feet (61 cm) wide.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] At almost all levels of competition, the top of the rim is exactly 10 feet (3.05 meters) above the court and 4 feet (1.22 meters) inside the baseline.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] While variation is possible in the dimensions of the court and backboard, it is considered important for the basket to be of the correct height – a rim that is off by just a few inches can have an adverse effect on shooting.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The net must "check the ball momentarily as it passes through the basket" to aid the visual confirmation that the ball went through.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The act of checking the ball has the further advantage of slowing down the ball so the rebound does not go as far.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The size of the basketball is also regulated.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] For men, the official ball is 29.5 inches (75 cm) in circumference (size 7, or a "295 ball") and weighs 22 oz (620 g).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If women are playing, the official basketball size is 28.5 inches (72 cm) in circumference (size 6, or a "285 ball") with a weight of 20 oz (570 g).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In 3x3, a formalized version of the halfcourt 3-on-3 game, a dedicated ball with the circumference of a size 6 ball but the weight of a size 7 ball is used in all competitions (men's, women's, and mixed teams).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The ball may be advanced toward the basket by being shot, passed between players, thrown, tapped, rolled or dribbled (bouncing the ball while running).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The ball must stay within the court; the last team to touch the ball before it travels out of bounds forfeits possession.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The ball is out of bounds if it touches a boundary line, or touches any player or object that is out of bounds.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] There are limits placed on the steps a player may take without dribbling, which commonly results in an infraction known as traveling.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Nor may a player stop their dribble and then resume dribbling.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A dribble that touches both hands is considered stopping the dribble, giving this infraction the name double dribble.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Within a dribble, the player cannot carry the ball by placing their hand on the bottom of the ball; doing so is known as carrying the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A team, once having established ball control in the front half of their court, may not return the ball to the backcourt and be the first to touch it.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A violation of these rules results in loss of possession.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The ball may not be kicked, nor be struck with the fist.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] For the offense, a violation of these rules results in loss of possession; for the defense, most leagues reset the shot clock and the offensive team is given possession of the ball out of bounds.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These rules are designed to promote more offense.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] There are also limits on how players may block an opponent's field goal attempt or help a teammate's field goal attempt.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Goaltending is a defender's touching of a ball that is on a downward flight toward the basket, while the related violation of basket interference is the touching of a ball that is on the rim or above the basket, or by a player reaching through the basket from below.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Goaltending and basket interference committed by a defender result in awarding the basket to the offense, while basket interference committed by an offensive player results in cancelling the basket if one is scored.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The defense gains possession in all cases of goaltending or basket interference.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] An attempt to unfairly disadvantage an opponent through certain types of physical contact is illegal and is called a personal foul.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These are most commonly committed by defensive players; however, they can be committed by offensive players as well.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Players who are fouled either receive the ball to pass inbounds again, or receive one or more free throws if they are fouled in the act of shooting, depending on whether the shot was successful.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] One point is awarded for making a free throw, which is attempted from a line 15 feet (4.6 m) from the basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The referee is responsible for judging whether contact is illegal, sometimes resulting in controversy.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] The calling of fouls can vary between games, leagues and referees.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] There is a second category of fouls called technical fouls, which may be charged for various rules violations including failure to properly record a player in the scorebook, or for unsportsmanlike conduct.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] These infractions result in one or two free throws, which may be taken by any of the five players on the court at the time.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] Repeated incidents can result in disqualification.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A blatant foul involving physical contact that is either excessive or unnecessary is called an intentional foul (flagrant foul in the NBA).
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In FIBA and NCAA women's basketball, a foul resulting in ejection is called a disqualifying foul, while in leagues other than the NBA, such a foul is referred to as flagrant.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If a team exceeds a certain limit of team fouls in a given period (quarter or half) – four for NBA, NCAA women's, and international games – the opposing team is awarded one or two free throws on all subsequent non-shooting fouls for that period, the number depending on the league.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In the US college men's game and high school games for both sexes, if a team reaches 7 fouls in a half, the opposing team is awarded one free throw, along with a second shot if the first is made.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If a team exceeds 10 fouls in the half, the opposing team is awarded two free throws on all subsequent fouls for the half.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] When a team shoots foul shots, the opponents may not interfere with the shooter, nor may they try to regain possession until the last or potentially last free throw is in the air.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] After a team has committed a specified number of fouls, the other team is said to be "in the bonus".
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] On scoreboards, this is usually signified with an indicator light reading "Bonus" or "Penalty" with an illuminated directional arrow or dot indicating that team is to receive free throws when fouled by the opposing team.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If a team misses the first shot of a two-shot situation, the opposing team must wait for the completion of the second shot before attempting to reclaim possession of the ball and continuing play.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If a player is fouled while attempting a shot and the shot is unsuccessful, the player is awarded a number of free throws equal to the value of the attempted shot.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] A player fouled while attempting a regular two-point shot thus receives two shots, and a player fouled while attempting a three-point shot receives three shots.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] If a player is fouled while attempting a shot and the shot is successful, typically the player will be awarded one additional free throw for one point.
[src:basketball/basketball-p01] In combination with a regular shot, this is called a "three-point play" or "four-point play" (or more colloquially, an "and one") because of the basket made at the time of the foul (2 or 3 points) and the additional free throw (1 point).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Although the rules do not specify any positions whatsoever, they have evolved as part of basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] During the early years of basketball's evolution, two guards, two forwards, and one center were used.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In more recent times, specific positions evolved, but the current trend, advocated by many top coaches including Mike Krzyzewski, is towards positionless basketball, where big players are free to shoot from outside and dribble if their skill allows it.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Point guard (often called the "**1**") : usually the fastest player on the team, organizes the team's offense by controlling the ball and making sure that it gets to the right player at the right time.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Shooting guard (the "**2**") : creates a high volume of shots on offense, mainly long-ranged; and guards the opponent's best perimeter player on defense.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Small forward (the "**3**") : often primarily responsible for scoring points via cuts to the basket and dribble penetration; on defense seeks rebounds and steals, but sometimes plays more actively.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Power forward (the "**4**"): plays offensively often with their back to the basket; on defense, plays under the basket (in a zone defense) or against the opposing power forward (in man-to-man defense).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Center (the "**5**"): uses height and size to score (on offense), to protect the basket closely (on defense), or to rebound.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] There are two main defensive strategies: *zone defense* and *man-to-man defense*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In a zone defense, each player is assigned to guard a specific area of the court.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Zone defenses often allow the defense to double team the ball, a maneuver known as a **trap**.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In a man-to-man defense, each defensive player guards a specific opponent.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Offensive plays are more varied, normally involving planned passes and movement by players without the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A quick movement by an offensive player without the ball to gain an advantageous position is known as a *cut*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A legal attempt by an offensive player to stop an opponent from guarding a teammate, by standing in the defender's way such that the teammate cuts next to him, is a *screen* or *pick*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The two plays are combined in the *pick and roll*, in which a player sets a pick and then "rolls" away from the pick towards the basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Screens and cuts are very important in offensive plays; these allow the quick passes and teamwork, which can lead to a successful basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Teams almost always have several offensive plays planned to ensure their movement is not predictable.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] On court, the point guard is usually responsible for indicating which play will occur.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Shooting is the act of attempting to score points by throwing the ball through the basket, methods varying with players and situations.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Typically, a player faces the basket with both feet facing the basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A player will rest the ball on the fingertips of the dominant hand (the shooting arm) slightly above the head, with the other hand supporting the side of the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The ball is usually shot by jumping (though not always) and extending the shooting arm.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The shooting arm, fully extended with the wrist fully bent, is held stationary for a moment following the release of the ball, known as a *follow-through*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Players often try to put a steady backspin on the ball to absorb its impact with the rim.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The ideal trajectory of the shot is somewhat controversial, but generally a proper arc is recommended.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Players may shoot directly into the basket or may use the backboard to redirect the ball into the basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The two most common shots that use the above described setup are the *set shot* and the *jump shot*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Both are preceded by a crouching action which preloads the muscles and increases the power of the shot.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In a set shot, the shooter straightens up and throws from a standing position with neither foot leaving the floor; this is typically used for free throws.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] For a jump shot, the throw is taken in mid-air with the ball being released near the top of the jump.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] This provides much greater power and range, and it also allows the player to elevate over the defender.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Failure to release the ball before the feet return to the floor is considered a traveling violation.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Another common shot is called the *layup*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] This shot requires the player to be in motion toward the basket, and to "lay" the ball "up" and into the basket, typically off the backboard (the backboard-free, underhand version is called a *finger roll*).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The most crowd-pleasing and typically highest-percentage accuracy shot is the *slam dunk*, in which the player jumps very high and throws the ball downward, through the basket while touching it.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Another shot, less common than the layup, is the "circus shot".
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The circus shot is a low-percentage shot that is flipped, heaved, scooped, or flung toward the hoop while the shooter is off-balance, airborne, falling down or facing away from the basket.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A back-shot is a shot taken when the player is facing away from the basket, and may be shot with the dominant hand, or both; but there is a very low chance that the shot will be successful.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A shot that misses both the rim and the backboard completely is referred to as an *air ball*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A particularly bad shot, or one that only hits the backboard, is jocularly called a brick.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The *hang time* is the length of time a player stays in the air after jumping, either to make a slam dunk, layup or jump shot.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The objective of rebounding is to successfully gain possession of the basketball after a missed field goal or free throw, as it rebounds from the hoop or backboard.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] This plays a major role in the game, as most possessions end when a team misses a shot.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] There are two categories of rebounds: offensive rebounds, in which the ball is recovered by the offensive side and does not change possession, and defensive rebounds, in which the defending team gains possession of the loose ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The majority of rebounds are defensive, as the team on defense tends to be in better position to recover missed shots; for example, about 75% of rebounds in the NBA are defensive.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A pass is a method of moving the ball between players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Most passes are accompanied by a step forward to increase power and are followed through with the hands to ensure accuracy.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The ball is passed directly from the passer's chest to the receiver's chest.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A proper chest pass involves an outward snap of the thumbs to add velocity and leaves the defence little time to react.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Another type of pass is the *bounce pass*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Here, the passer bounces the ball crisply about two-thirds of the way from his own chest to the receiver.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The ball strikes the court and bounces up toward the receiver.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The bounce pass takes longer to complete than the chest pass, but it is also harder for the opposing team to intercept (kicking the ball deliberately is a violation).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Thus, players often use the bounce pass in crowded moments, or to pass around a defender.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The *overhead pass* is used to pass the ball over a defender.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The ball is released while over the passer's head.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The *outlet pass* occurs after a team gets a defensive rebound.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The next pass after the rebound is the *outlet pass*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The crucial aspect of any good pass is it being difficult to intercept.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Good passers can pass the ball with great accuracy and they know exactly where each of their other teammates prefers to receive the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A special way of doing this is passing the ball without looking at the receiving teammate.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Another advanced style of passing is the *behind-the-back pass*, which, as the description implies, involves throwing the ball behind the passer's back to a teammate.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Although some players can perform such a pass effectively, many coaches discourage no-look or behind-the-back passes, believing them to be difficult to control and more likely to result in turnovers or violations.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Dribbling is the act of bouncing the ball continuously with one hand and is a requirement for a player to take steps with the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] To dribble, a player pushes the ball down towards the ground with the fingertips rather than patting it; this ensures greater control.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] When dribbling past an opponent, the dribbler should dribble with the hand farthest from the opponent, making it more difficult for the defensive player to get to the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] It is therefore important for a player to be able to dribble competently with both hands.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Good dribblers (or "ball handlers") tend to keep their dribbling hand low to the ground, reducing the distance of travel of the ball from the floor to the hand, making it more difficult for the defender to "steal" the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Good ball handlers frequently dribble behind their backs, between their legs, and switch directions suddenly, making a less predictable dribbling pattern that is more difficult to defend against.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] This is called a crossover, which is the most effective way to move past defenders while dribbling.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A skilled player can dribble without watching the ball, using the dribbling motion or peripheral vision to keep track of the ball's location.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] By not having to focus on the ball, a player can look for teammates or scoring opportunities, as well as avoid the danger of having someone steal the ball away from him/her.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] A block is performed when, after a shot is attempted, a defender succeeds in altering the shot by touching the ball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In almost all variants of play, it is illegal to touch the ball after it is in the downward path of its arc; this is known as *goaltending*.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] It is also illegal under the NBA and Men's NCAA basketball to block a shot after it has touched the backboard, or when any part of the ball is directly above the rim.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Under international rules it is illegal to block a shot that is in the downward path of its arc or one that has touched the backboard until the ball has hit the rim.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] After the ball hits the rim, it is again legal to touch it even though it is no longer considered as a block performed.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] To block a shot, a player has to be able to reach a point higher than where the shot is released.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Thus, height can be an advantage in blocking.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Players who are taller and playing the power forward or center positions generally record more blocks than players who are shorter and playing the guard positions.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] However, with good timing and a sufficiently high vertical leap, even shorter players can be effective shot blockers.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] At the professional level, most male players are above 6 feet 3 inches (1.91 m) and most women above 5 feet 7 inches (1.70 m).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Guards, for whom physical coordination and ball-handling skills are crucial, tend to be the smallest players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Almost all forwards in the top men's pro leagues are 6 feet 6 inches (1.98 m) or taller.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Most centers are over 6 feet 10 inches (2.08 m) tall.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] According to a survey given to all NBA teams, the average height of all NBA players with shoes on is around 6 feet 6 inches (1.98 m), although exaggeration of height is widespread.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The average weight is close to 222 pounds (101 kg).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The tallest players ever in the NBA were Manute Bol and Gheorghe Mureșan, who were both 7 feet 7 inches (2.31 m) tall.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] At 7 feet 2 inches (2.18 m), Margo Dydek was the tallest player in the history of the WNBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The shortest player ever to play in the NBA is Muggsy Bogues at 5 feet 3 inches (1.60 m).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Other average-height or relatively short players have thrived at the pro level, including Anthony "Spud" Webb, who was 5 feet 7 inches (1.70 m) tall, but had a 42-inch (1.1 m) vertical leap, giving him significant height when jumping.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] There was also Yuki Kawamura, who stood at 5 ft 8 in (1.73 m), found success with the Japan men's national basketball team, with him averaging 20 points, 3 rebounds, and 7 assists with his team.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] His success with his national team led him to sign a two-way deal with the Memphis Grizzlies of the NBA.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Lastly, Temeka Johnson, who won the WNBA Rookie of the Year Award and a championship with the Phoenix Mercury while standing only 5 feet 3 inches (1.60 m).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] While shorter players are often at a disadvantage in certain aspects of the game, their ability to navigate quickly through crowded areas of the court and steal the ball by reaching low is a strength.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Players regularly inflate their height in high school or college.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Many prospects exaggerate their height while in high school or college to make themselves more appealing to coaches and scouts, who prefer taller players.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Charles Barkley stated; "I've been measured at 6–5, 6-4+3⁄4.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] But I started in college at 6–6." Sam Smith, a former writer from the *Chicago Tribune*, said: "We sort of know the heights, because after camp, the sheet comes out.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] But you use that height, and the player gets mad.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Or you file your story with the right height, and the copy desk changes it because they have the 'official' N.B.A. media guide, which is wrong.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Since the 2019–20 NBA season, heights of NBA players are recorded definitively by measuring players with their shoes off.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Variations of basketball are activities based on the game of basketball, using common basketball skills and equipment (primarily the ball and basket).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Some variations only have superficial rule changes, while others are distinct games with varying degrees of influence from basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Other variations include children's games, contests or activities meant to help players reinforce skills.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] An earlier version of basketball, played primarily by women and girls, was six-on-six basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Horseball is a game played on horseback where a ball is handled and points are scored by shooting it through a high net (approximately 1.5m×1.5m).
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The sport is like a combination of polo, rugby, and basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] There is even a form played on donkeys known as Donkey basketball, which has attracted criticism from animal rights groups.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Perhaps the single most common variation of basketball is the half-court game, played in informal settings without referees or strict rules.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Only one basket is used, and the ball must be "taken back" or "cleared" – passed or dribbled outside the three-point line each time possession of the ball changes from one team to the other.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Half-court games require less cardiovascular stamina, since players need not run back and forth a full court.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Half-court raises the number of players that can use a court or, conversely, can be played if there is an insufficient number to form full 5-on-5 teams.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Half-court basketball is usually played 1-on-1, 2-on-2, or 3-on-3.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The last of these variations is gradually gaining official recognition as 3x3, originally known as FIBA 33.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] It was first tested at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau and the first official tournaments were held at the 2009 Asian Youth Games and the 2010 Youth Olympics, both in Singapore.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The first FIBA 3x3 Youth World Championships were held in Rimini, Italy in 2011, with the first FIBA 3x3 World Championships for senior teams following a year later in Athens.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The sport is highly tipped to become an Olympic sport as early as 2016.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] In the summer of 2017, the BIG3 basketball league, a professional 3x3 half court basketball league that features former NBA players, began.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] The BIG3 features several rule variants including a four-point field goal.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Basketball as a social and communal sport features environments, rules and demographics different from those seen in professional and televised basketball.
[src:basketball/basketball-p02] Basketball is played widely as an extracurricular, intramural or amateur sport in schools and colleges.
